## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests — 0 reliable.** This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called, which produces ~95% line coverage, but almost nothing is actually verified. Bugs in pricing, search, CSV parsing, and removal would all sail through these tests.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| 🔴 Critical | 6 |
| 🟡 Medium | 2 |
| ⚪ Low | 1 |

---

### 🔴 Critical — Tests giving false confidence

#### 1. Coverage-touching (systemic)
**All 10 tests, lines 17–89**

The class methodically calls every public method on `ProductCatalog` with no meaningful assertions. 5 tests have **zero assertions**; the other 5 use only `Assert.IsNotNull()` on types that can never be null by design (`List<T>`, `string`). This inflates coverage to ~95% while verifying nothing.

---

#### 2. No assertions — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)
Calls `AddProduct` but never checks the product was actually stored.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_Works()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);

    var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
}
```

---

#### 3. No assertions — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)
Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price changed. A bug returning the old price would pass.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_Works()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

    var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
}
```

---

#### 4. No assertions — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39)
Calls `RemoveProduct` but never checks the product is gone. A no-op `Delete` would pass.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void RemoveProduct_Works()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");

    Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
}
```

---

#### 5. No assertions — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)
Calls `GetProductCount()`, throws away the result. Can't detect off-by-one or always-zero bugs.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetProductCount_Works()
{
    Assert.AreEqual(0, _catalog.GetProductCount());

